'''Mees' lines''' or '''Aldrich–Mees' lines''', also called [[leukonychia]] striata, are lines of discoloration across the [[Nail (anatomy)|nails]] of the [[finger]]s and [[toe]]s.

== Causes ==
Mees' lines appear after an episode of [[poison]]ing with [[arsenic]],<ref name="pmid11869818">{{cite journal |author=Hall AH |title=Chronic arsenic poisoning |journal=Toxicol. Lett. |volume=128 |issue=1–3 |pages=69–72 |year=2002 |pmid=11869818 |doi=10.1016/S0378-4274(01)00534-3}}</ref> [[thallium]] or other heavy metals, and can also appear if the subject is suffering from [[renal failure]].<ref name="pmid16707817">{{cite journal |author=Udayakumar P, Balasubramanian S, Ramalingam KS, Lakshmi C, Srinivas CR, Mathew AC |title=Cutaneous manifestations in patients with chronic renal failure on hemodialysis |journal=Indian journal of dermatology, venereology and leprology |volume=72 |issue=2 |pages=119–25 |year=2006 |pmid=16707817 |doi=10.4103/0378-6323.25636}}</ref> They have been observed in chemotherapy patients.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Huang|first=T.-C.|coauthors=Chao, T.-Y.|title=Mees lines and Beau lines after chemotherapy|journal=Canadian Medical Association Journal|date=14 December 2009|volume=182|issue=3|pages=E149–E149|doi=10.1503/cmaj.090501|accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref>

== Presentation ==
They are typically white bands traversing the width of the nail. As the nail grows they move towards the end, and finally disappear when trimmed.

== Eponym and history ==
Although the phenomenon is named after Dutch physician R.A. Mees, who described the abnormality in 1919,<ref>{{cite journal | author=Mees RA | title=Een verschijnsel bij polyneuritis arsenicosa | language=Dutch | journal=Ned Tijdsch Geneeskd | year=1919 | volume=1 | pages=391–396}}</ref> earlier descriptions of the same abnormality were made by Englishman E. S. Reynolds in 1901<ref>{{cite journal | author=Reynolds ES | title=An Account of the Epidemic Outbreak of Arsenical Poisoning occurring in Beer Drinkers in the North of England and the Midland Counties in 1900 | journal=Lancet | year=1901 | volume=1 | pages=166–70 | doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(01)81229-0 | pmc=2036791 | pmid=20896969 | issue=4038}}</ref> and by American C. J. Aldrich in 1904.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Aldrich CJ | title=Leuconychia striata arsenicalis transversus, with report of three cases | journal=Am J Med Sci | year=1904 | volume =127 | pages=702–709 | doi=10.1097/00000441-190412740-00014 | issue=4}}</ref>

